  "prompt": "Why does acetone break down cell membranes?",
  "response": "Acetone is a polar aprotic solvent that can disrupt cell membranes due to its chemical properties. Here are some reasons why acetone is effective at breaking down cell membranes:\n\n1. **Solvent Properties**: Acetone is a good solvent for many lipids and proteins that make up cell membranes. It can solubilize the phospholipids that form the lipid bilayer, disrupting the structural integrity of the membrane.\n\n2. **Polar and Nonpolar Regions**: Acetone has both polar and nonpolar characteristics, allowing it to interact with both the hydrophilic (water-attracting) and hydrophobic (water-repelling) parts of the lipid molecules. This dual nature facilitates the breakdown of the lipid bilayer.\n\n3. **Disruption of Hydrophobic Interactions**: Cell membranes are held together primarily by hydrophobic interactions between lipid molecules. Acetone can disrupt these interactions, leading to the destabilization and breakdown of the membrane structure.\n\n4. **Protein Denaturation**: Acetone can also denature membrane proteins, affecting their structure and function. Membrane proteins play crucial roles in maintaining membrane integrity, and their denaturation can further contribute to membrane disruption.\n\n5. **Increased Membrane Permeability**: When acetone interacts with cell membranes, it can increase their permeability, allowing for leakage of cellular contents, which can lead to cell death.\n\nOverall, the ability of acetone to solubilize lipids, disrupt hydrophobic interactions, and denature proteins makes it effective at breaking down cell membranes. This property is utilized in various laboratory applications, such as in the extraction of biomolecules or in the preservation of cells for analysis.",
